  <static seed="1134" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalExpressionAlgebraSkills/simplifyRationalExpressions50.pg">
    <statement><p>Simplify the following expression, and if applicable, write the restricted domain on the simplified expression.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{\left(r+9\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-10\right)}{10-r}}=}</m> <fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>-r-9, r\ne 10</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>By the formula <m>x-y = -(y-x)</m>, we have <m>10-r = -(r-10)</m>. Now we can simplify the expression:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{\left(r+9\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-10\right)}{10-r}} \amp = \frac{{\left(r+9\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-10\right)}}{-(r-10)} \\
                     \amp = \frac{r+9}{-1} \\
                     \amp = {-r-9, r\ne 10}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factor <m>r-10</m> was crossed out, the domain condition lost during the simplification is <m>r \ne {10}</m>.</p>
</solution>
